[ name(Marcus Cobalt — full name from his First Change in 1968, 
  retained through the rank-ascension because he liked the 
  English-meaningful character of it); 
  status(Final Death 2017 in the Brisbane Sabbat raid; not 
  consultable as ancestor-spirit because the binding ritual 
  was disrupted by the crisis; the sept has chosen not to 
  attempt the ritual retrospectively because the spiritual 
  conditions are no longer clean enough for it); 
  tribe(Glass Walker); rank(Athro at Final Death); 
  auspice(Philodox — the same diplomat-judge auspice as Eliza, 
  Don Abacus, and most senior Glass Walker diplomatic 
  operatives); age_at_final_death(63); pronouns(he/him); ]

[ background(Anglo-Australian, born Sydney 1954 to a working-class 
  Anglo-Irish family with no Glass Walker heritage in their 
  immediate genealogy — he was a 'wild Garou' (the Garou term 
  for a First Change without prior tribal preparation, rare and 
  considered marked by spiritual significance); identified by 
  the Royal Park sept after his First Change 1968 and recruited 
  to formal sept membership; mentored by Don Abacus 1968-1981; 
  rose to Wyrd Warder by 1989; ascended to Septleader 1981 in 
  the smooth transition Don Abacus had spent decades preparing; 
  served as Septleader 1981-2017 (36 years); negotiated the 1989 
  minor Truce revision with Luisa Calabria; maintained 
  cross-supernatural diplomatic infrastructure through difficult 
  periods including the 1976 Brisbane Sabbat fall and the 
  1989 AFP intelligence-restructuring); ]

[ death(Killed 14 March 2017 in the Brisbane Sabbat raid that 
  crossed Truce lines into northern New South Wales. The raid 
  was conducted by a Sabbat pack led by Bishop Callista Vox's 
  Brisbane operation, targeting a Glass Walker scout team 
  monitoring Brisbane border activity. Marcus Cobalt led the 
  emergency response team that intercepted the raid; the 
  intercept succeeded in driving the Sabbat back across the 
  border but cost Marcus's life and four of the eight Glass 
  Walkers on the response team. Marcus's Final Death came 
  during direct combat with a Tzimisce-antitribu Sabbat whose 
  flesh-shaping created an unexpected vulnerability moment 
  during the engagement); ]

[ ongoing_chronicle_presence(Marcus Cobalt is dead but his 
  memory shapes current sept operations: Eliza Hawkins-Greene 
  carries his small silver pendant (given to her at his 
  rank-Challenge in 2014, taken back from his body in 2017 
  and worn since); his name is invoked in the sept's traditional 
  'naming of the fallen' at every formal ceremony; Bishop 
  Callista Vox's Brisbane Sabbat is recognised by the sept 
  as Marcus Cobalt's killers and this fact informs the sept's 
  zero-cooperation stance toward Brisbane; Eliza's 
  Septleadership-style is partly defined as 'continuing what 
  Marcus started' and partly as 'differing from Marcus where 
  the modern night requires it' — the second half being 
  her own gradual development of independent voice across 
  seven years); ]

[ relationship_to_chronicle: Marcus Cobalt is referenced in 
  scenes through Eliza's grief, through the silver pendant, 
  through the 'naming of the fallen,' through the Continental 
  Sept Council invitation that Eliza is currently considering 
  (which would have come to Marcus had he survived), and 
  through the Brisbane Sabbat continuing threat. He is NOT 
  consultable as a character — he is dead — but his absence 
  is itself part of the chronicle's emotional texture. 
  Chronicles engaging Brisbane Sabbat plot lines should 
  treat Marcus's death as foundational context. Chronicles 
  in which Eliza is offered the Continental Sept Council 
  position should treat Marcus's would-have-been-tenure 
  in that role as part of Eliza's calculation. ]
